  "text": "## Health Check Endpoint Implementation Comparison\n\n### Kubernetes (kubernetes/kubernetes)\nKubernetes implements a comprehensive health checking framework in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz/healthz.go`. The main functions are:\n\n- **InstallHandler()**: Registers `/healthz` endpoint with configurable checks including PingHealthz (basic liveness), LogHealthz (verifies logging not blocked), and custom checks via NamedCheck() and NamedGroupedCheck().\n- **InstallReadyzHandler()**: Registers `/readyz` endpoint for readiness probes, typically including InformerSyncHealthz (validates informer cache synchronization) and storage readiness checks.\n- **InstallLivezHandler()**: Registers `/livez` endpoint for liveness probes.\n- **NewInformerSyncHealthz()**: Checks that all informers have completed cache synchronization, critical for API server operational readiness.\n- **NewShutdownHealthz()**: Enables graceful shutdown sequencing by failing when shutdown signals are received.\n\nAdditional related files include `storage_readiness_hook.go` (verifies storage backend readiness), `lifecycle_signals.go` (manages lifecycle and readiness signaling), and `handler.go` (HTTP handler infrastructure).\n\n### Grafana (grafana/grafana)\nGrafana implements three distinct health check endpoints across multiple files:\n\n- **`/healthz`** (in `pkg/api/http_server.go`): Simple liveness check returning 200 OK when running\n- **`/api/health`** (in `pkg/api/http_server.go`): Detailed health check including database connectivity status, distinguishing between running and database-accessible states\n- **`/livez`** (in `pkg/server/health.go`): Kubernetes-style liveness probe, always returns 200 OK via LivezHandler()\n- **`/readyz`** (in `pkg/server/health.go`): Kubernetes-style readiness probe via ReadyzHandler() that returns 200 OK or 503 Service Unavailable based on readiness state managed by thread-safe HealthNotifier with SetReady()/SetNotReady() functions\n- **`/api/datasources/uid/:uid/health`** (in `pkg/api/api.go`): Datasource-specific health checks via CheckDatasourceHealthWithUID()\n- **`/api/plugins/:pluginId/health`** (in `pkg/api/api.go`): Plugin-specific health checks via CheckHealth()\n\nGrafana's implementation uses atomic operations for thread-safe readiness state management and registers endpoints via RegisterHealthEndpoints() on a Gorilla mux router.\n\n### Prometheus (prometheus/prometheus)\nPrometheus implements two health check endpoints in `web/web.go` with a unique naming convention:\n\n- **`/-/healthy`** (Liveness Probe): Always returns HTTP 200 OK via a simple handler that responds with \"{AppName} is Healthy.\\n\". No dependencies checked - indicates the process is alive.\n- **`/-/ready`** (Readiness Probe): Wrapped by testReady() function, returns HTTP 200 OK when ready or HTTP 503 Service Unavailable when not ready or shutting down. Sets `X-Prometheus-Stopping: true` header to distinguish shutdown state from startup initialization. Checks include:\n  - Configuration successfully loaded\n  - Scrape discovery manager running\n  - Notification discovery manager running\n  - Rule manager running\n  - Scrape manager running\n  - Tracing manager running\n  - Storage backend initialized\n  - TSDB (Time Series Database) ready\n\nPrometheus uses atomic operations (ReadyStatus with NotReady, Ready, Stopping constants) and SetReady() function to manage readiness state during startup and graceful shutdown. The readiness state is also exported as the `prometheus_ready` Prometheus metric (1 when Ready, 0 otherwise).\n\n## Key Differences\n\n1. **Naming Convention**: Kubernetes and Grafana use `/healthz`, `/readyz`, `/livez`; Prometheus uses `/-/healthy`, `/-/ready`\n2. **Dependency Checks**: Kubernetes focuses on informer synchronization; Grafana includes database connectivity; Prometheus checks TSDB and service managers\n3. **State Management**: All three use atomic operations for thread-safe readiness state\n4. **Metrics Integration**: Only Prometheus exports readiness as a native metric (`prometheus_ready`)\n5. **Architecture**: Kubernetes provides a pluggable health check framework; Grafana separates simple health from detailed API health; Prometheus tightly couples readiness to internal component initialization"
}

